env - print environment variable
$VARIABLE=$VALUE - change environment variable
echo $VARIABLE - print a variable
/etc/environment file contains global variables
.bashrc file contains user-specific variables
/etc/profile.d/ directory contains scripts that will be run on any :"user login
/etc/skel folder contains a template for new users' home directories and environments

to make Bash search for a command associated with a program you installed, you should add it to your
PATH variable. The program's directory has to be preceded and ended with a colon ':YOUR/PATH:'. Then
you can run your program straight from bash terminal instance.
